We have recommended that management implement the following measures to ensure the reliability of the balances of PPE accounts and records:

Physical inventory of fixed assets shall be made at least once a year;
the Inventory Committee prepare the Physical Inventory Reports to be submitted to the Property Officer for verification and reconciliation with the records maintained by the Accounting Office and the property cards of the Property Unit;
Establishment of property identification and coding;
Maintenance of the Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment to establish the   official accountable for the property;
Reclassification of unserviceable property noted during the physical count of inventory to Other Assets and conduct a proper disposal of unserviceable property; and
PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards should be maintained and updated by the respective offices in accordance with the NGAS Manual for LGU.

Non-submission of duly prepared Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC) for the Procurement of Infrastructure Projects

The Municipality did not prepare and submit its Annual Procurement Plan (APP) to serve as guide in the procurement of infrastructure projects in violation of Section 7.1 of the Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations of Republic Act No. 9184.

Complete bidding documents were not submitted as prescribed by the GPPB.

Pre-procurement Conference was not conducted for Infrastructure Projects with Approved Budget for the Contract exceeding ₱5 million.

Posting requirements were not adhered to for the procurement of goods and infrastructure projects with ABC totaling ₱47,655,038.80. 

Non-submission of the Minutes of pre-bid conference, Minutes of Opening of Bids and the corresponding Attendance sheet as indication of the non-conduct of said undertakings contrary to Section 22 and Section 29 of the Revised IRR of R.A. 9184.

Contracts review of projects with ABC totaling ₱46,955,038.80 undertaken through public bidding showed that in all stages of the procurement process, the Bids and Awards Committee did not invite in writing the presence of observers including the COA Audit Team.

Contracts were awarded despite absence of contractor’s eligibility requirements and other bidding documents indicating that the members of the Bids and Awards Committee did not conduct a thorough evaluation of the documents submitted by the bidder/contractor, in violation of the provisions of the IRR of R.A. 9184.

Contracts were awarded despite non-submission of the contractor’s Performance Security and other contract documents in violation of Section 37 and Section 39 of the IRR of R.A. 9184. 

Contract agreement for the procurement of medical supplies with contract amount of ₱823,500.00 was not submitted.

Non-adherence to the posting requirement in the PhilGEPS of the Notice of Award and Notice to Proceed for contracts totaling ₱47,655,038.80

In view of the above observations, we have recommended the following:

the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Engineer to prepare the ABC for each infrastructure project of the Municipality;
the Municipal Mayor instruct the department heads to prepare their PPMP to be consolidated by the BAC Secretariat into the APP and the Municipal Budget Officer should ensure that the APP is consistent with the duly approved yearly budget;
the BAC observe the required pre-procurement conference for infrastructure project with an ABC above ₱5,000,000.00;
the BAC, through its BAC Secretariat observe the proper advertising and posting of the Invitation to Bid as prescribed in the Revised IRR of R.A. 9184 to encourage more participants in the bidding process and intensify the competition among them, which in turn, will ensure that the LGU will get the best possible proposals, as to quality and cost, for the project sought to be procured;
the BAC observe the bidding process and prepare the necessary records and reports as support to the contract and bidding documents;
the BAC invite in writing observers to observe in the procurement activities of the Municipality;
the members of the BAC submit justification/ explanation on the noted violations and ensure that prospective bidders submit complete eligibility requirements and post the necessary bid security before they are marked as “passed” and declared as LCB and require the prospective bidders post the required performance security prior to contract signing; 
the BAC secretariat submit the noted bidding documents; and
the BAC members should attend trainings on updates on the different provisions of the Government Procurement Law or R.A. 9184.

We have recommended that management ensure that:

the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer see to it that Disbursement Vouchers for government contracts are duly and properly supported before payment pursuant to Section 4.6 of PD No. 1445;

adopt public bidding as the general mode of procurement and shall see to it that the procurement program allows sufficient lead time for such public bidding.

We have recommended that:

the ICO Municipal Treasurer record the verified reconciling items from previous years;
the Municipal Accountant, Designate and ICO Municipal Treasurer trace back transactions of prior periods to account for the un-reconciled difference in the books before recording the adjustments;
the Municipal Accountant, Designate prepare the reconciliation statements for the trust fund accounts individually; and
henceforth, the Municipal Accountant, Designate and ICO Municipal Treasurer reconcile monthly the accounting with the treasury and the bank records to immediately detect errors and verify the correctness and accuracy of their records.

We have recommended that:

the Municipal Treasurer record the verified reconciling items from previous years;
the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer trace back transactions of prior periods to account for the un-reconciled difference in the trust fund books;
the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer reconcile monthly the accounting with the treasury and the bank records to immediately detect errors and ensure the correctness and accuracy of their records.

In view of the above observations, we have recommended the following:

That the Local Chief Executive instruct the GAD Focal Point to identify programs, projects and activities that address gender issues such as promotion of gender-responsive governance, protection and fulfillment of women’s human rights and promotion of women’s economic empowerment to be included in the GAD Plan;
That the Local Chief Executive ensure that the procedures of submission, review and approval of LGU GAD Plan and Budget are complied;
That the GAD Focal Point conform to the prescribed format of GAD Plan and Budget and Annual GAD Accomplishment Report;
That management ensure the immediate submission of the noted missing disbursement voucher with the complete liquidation documents and the Resolution on the Realignment of the GAD fund ; and
That management submits justification for the utilization of the GAD fund to non-GAD responsive programs.

We have recommended that management implement the following measures to assure the reliability of the balances of PPE accounts and records:
a. Physical inventory of fixed assets shall be made at least once a year;
b. Establishment of property identification and coding;
c. Maintenance of the Acknowledgement Receipt of Equipment to establish the official accountable for the property;
d. Reconciliation of the inventory report with the balances reflected in the financial statements, identification of persons accountable for loss of property and proper recording of adjustments in the financial statements;
e. Reclassification of unserviceable property noted during the physical count of inventory to Other Assets; and
f. Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards and Property Cards should be maintained and updated by the respective offices in accordance with the NGAS Manual for LGU.

In view of the foregoing observations, we have recommended the following:
1) that the Municipal Mayor directs the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Engineer to see to it that Disbursement Vouchers for government infrastructure projects are duly and properly supported before payments are made;
2) that the municipality consider the procurement of repairs and maintenance on equipment through competitive bidding;
3) that management submit the lacking supporting documents; and
4) henceforth, the Municipal Accountant ensures that all disbursements are with complete supporting documents and submitted within the reglementary period.

